You were probably aching, wanting not to die. Your body transformed. I couldn't bear to look so I turned my head.
Here, where I sit the next October, still seeing your eyes, pleading and afraid.
I watched you die in this room, then I gave your clothes away. I'm sorry, I had to.
We will ride over water With your ghost underneath the boat. What was you is now burnt bones and I cannot be at home.
You had cancer and you were killed and I'm left living like this, crying on the logging roads with your ashes in a jar.
Thinking about the things I'll tell you When you get back from wherever it is that you've gone.
But then I remember death is real and I'm still here.
You've been dead for one month and three days, and we are sleeping in the forest.
Nothing dies here. But here is where I came to grieve, to dive into it with you, with your absence.
