# Advice
#
Quiet and sincere sympathy is often the most welcome and efficient consolation to the afflicted.
Even if you don't know what to say, the fact that you are there does provide some comfort.
Offer a hug and a shoulder to cry on.
It's not easy, that's why it's needed.
Acknowledge the loss in an honest way.
Speak directly. Don't use euphemisms like passed on.
Don't cry as it will upset your mother.
Grief is about a broken heart, yet often we speak to people's intellect as opposed to their heart.
There will be a time for you to share, but not right now. Your role is to listen and stay with the person's loss.
As adults, we often mistakenly believe we can protect children by withholding information from them.
Share fond memories of the deceased. Do not make a name taboo. The bereaved need very much to talk it out and they may love to hear stories of their lost one. 
Be patient IF they retell the same story over-and-over. Story-telling is part of the healing process.
Bereavement can make us feel helpless and awkward. It's okay to be honest about it.
You can not fix things, so don't offer advice.
Be a good listener.
For some it will take months to separate from the physical body. For others, only minutes.
Death is as uniques as the person experiencing it.
The actual dying process often begins within the two weeks prior to death.
There is a shift in a person that takes them to a true comprehension and belief in their own mortality.
embrace the significance of this inevitable transition with courage and grace.
By comprehending the stages and signs of the end-of-life process, caregivers can alleviate some of the fear and uncertainty that often accompany this time.
A time of withdrawl, inside there is sorting out, evaluating one's life. 
But inside there is only room for one.
Processing one's life is usually done with eyes closed so sleep increases.
Spending more time asleep than awake becomes the norm.
Words lose their importance. Words are part of the physical life that is being left behind.
Touch takes on more meaning.
Appetite diminishes significantly, and eventually, eating and drinking cease altogether.
This is a normal part of the dying process, as the body no longer requires the sustenance it once did.
It can be distressing to witness, but it's a typical sign.
The dying person might also experience changes in circulation, leading to coolness and discoloration of the skin.
It's important for caregivers to remain calm and patient during these times, offering reassurance and gentle presence.
In the final days and hours of life, awareness often decreases further. Coma-like states become common, and the dying person might slip in and out of consciousness.
At this stage, many caregivers struggle with feelings of helplessness.
Breathing patterns can alter significantly; this is commonly known as Cheyne-Stokes respiration, characterized by periods of rapid breathing followed by pauses.
remember that providing a peaceful and comforting environment can be one of the best ways to support a loved one.
Caregivers should seek the guidance of healthcare professionals to manage pain and other symptoms effectively.
offer appropriate care while respecting the dying person's journey.
contribute to a more peaceful and dignified passing.
The emotional and psychological journey of letting go is a deeply personal and multifaceted experience for those who are facing the end of their life.
This withdrawal is a natural part of the process and can manifest in various forms, such as a decreased interest in activities that once brought joy, a desire for solitude, and a diminished engagement with loved ones.
often mistaken for depression, these changes reflect the dying person's need to conserve energy and focus on their internal experience.
These altered states of consciousness can include vivid dreams, hallucinations, or moments of clarity and lucidity.
Many dying people experience periods of confusion or disorientation as their mind begins to let go of the physical world.
Offering emotional support to a dying person requires sensitivity and empathy. 
Listening without judgment and allowing them to express their feelings and fears is crucial.
Recognizing the common physical changes and symptoms that occur as death approaches can help caregivers remain calm and focused.
Emotional support is crucial.
suggest simple yet meaningful gestures such as reading to the loved one, playing their favorite music, or sharing stories and memories.
Maintaining self-care is pivotal for caregivers, who often face immense stress and emotional strain.
a routine that includes regular breaks, nutritious meals, and some form of relaxation, like meditation or a walk, can be greatly beneficial.
The act of caregiving should not come at the expense of the caregiver's own health and wellbeing.
Equally important is the acknowledgment that caregivers cannot do it all alone.
Professional assistance from hospice care providers can offer specialized knowledge and alleviate some of the caregiving burdens.
Hospice teams often provide not only medical care but also emotional and spiritual support, giving caregivers much-needed respite and guidance.
be there for someone at their most vulnerable, offering not just care but companionship and love.
Soft lighting, soothing music, and minimizing loud and sudden noises can establish a serene atmosphere.
Familiar and cherished belongings, such as photographs, favorite blankets, or personal mementos, can provide comfort and a sense of home.
It is crucial to engage in conversations about their beliefs, values, and any unresolved issues they might wish to address, helping them find peace and closure.
Open and honest discussions about their preferences for their care and environment can help ensure their dignity is maintained.
Empowering the dying to make these choices, acknowledges their autonomy and respects their desires during this profound time.
the presence of family and friends can be comforting only if it aligns with the wishes of the dying person.
Limiting the number of visitors and scheduling visits can help balance the need for connection with the need for rest and privacy.
When a loved one passes away, the initial moments and hours can be overwhelming, filled with a blend of grief and the need to take immediate, necessary actions.
One of the first actions after a death occurs is to notify the appropriate authorities.
officially pronounce the death, a necessary step before taking further action.
Once the death has been legally pronounced, the next steps involve contacting a funeral home or mortuary.
The funeral home will handle transporting the body, preparing necessary documents, and guiding you through further arrangements.
Legal and logistical arrangements can feel daunting but are crucial to handle promptly. Begin by securing important documents such as the death certificate.
contemplate death not as an ending but as a natural transition — an intrinsic part of the human journey that is both daunting and deeply meaningful.
Understanding the natural process of dying can radically alter our perception of death.
She emphasizes that when we accept death as a part of life, we can provide more compassionate care and find solace in the experience.
shift their focus from the fear of loss to the opportunity for connection.
find personal meaning and acceptance in the face of loss.
the process of dying can be a profoundly spiritual journey, not only for the person who is passing but also for their loved ones.
engage in open conversations about death, share fears, and explore beliefs about mortality.
By facing these topics head-on, we can demystify death and approach it with a sense of calm and prepared acceptance.
extend kindness not only to the dying but also to yourself as you navigate emotions and experiences.
finding meaning in the journey of life and death is an essential part of the human experience.
Although you might feel relief at not having to deal with the situation, your friend will know that you didn't acknowledge their great loss. 
They may feel hurt or abandoned, just because you were afraid of saying the wrong thing.
The five stages, denial, anger, bargaining, depression, and acceptance are a part of the framework that makes up our learning to live with the one we lost.
The five stages are tools to help us frame and identify what we may be feeling. 
But the stages are not stops on some linear timeline in grief. Not everyone goes through all of them or in a prescribed order.
Denial is the first of the five stages of grief.
Denial helps us to survive the loss. In this stage, the world becomes meaningless and overwhelming. Life makes no sense.
We go numb. We wonder how we can go on, if we can go on, why we should go on.
Denial helps us to pace our feelings of grief. There is a grace in denial. It is nature's way of letting in only as much as we can handle.
As you accept the reality of the loss and start to ask yourself questions, you are unknowingly beginning the healing process.
As you proceed, all the feelings you were denying begin to surface.
Anger is a necessary stage of the healing process.
Be willing to feel your anger, even though it may seem endless. The more you truly feel it, the more it will begin to dissipate and the more you will heal.
There are many other emotions under the anger and you will get to them in time.
The truth is that anger has no limits. It can extend not only to your friends, the doctors, your family, yourself and your loved one who died, but also to God.
Underneath anger is pain, your pain.
It is natural to feel deserted and abandoned.
Anger is strength and it can be an anchor, giving temporary structure to the nothingness of loss.
Grief feels like being lost at sea.
The anger becomes a bridge over the open sea. It is something to hold onto.
Before a loss, it seems like you will do anything if only your loved one would be spared.
Guilt is often bargaining's companion. The 'if onlys' cause us to find fault in ourselves and what we think we could have done differently.
Would you do anything not to feel the pain of this loss?
The stages are responses to feelings that can last for minutes or hours as we flip in and out of one and then another.
We remain in the past, trying to negotiate our way out of the hurt.
Empty feelings present themselves, and grief enters our lives on a deeper level, deeper than we ever imagined.
This depressive stage feels as though it will last forever.
Depression is the appropriate response to a great loss.
We withdraw from life, left in a fog of intense sadness, wondering, perhaps, if there is any point in going on.
Depression after a loss is too often seen as unnatural.
The first question to ask yourself is whether or not the situation you're in is actually depressing. The loss of a loved one is a very depressing situation.
Depression is a normal and appropriate response.
When a loss fully settles in your soul, the realization that your loved one didn't get better this time and is not coming back is understandably depressing.
Acceptance is often confused with the notion of being all right or ok with what has happened. This is not the case.
Most people don't ever feel OK or all right about the loss of a loved one.
Acceptance is about accepting the reality that our loved one is physically gone and recognizing that this new reality is the permanent reality.
We will never like this reality or make it OK, but eventually we accept it. We learn to live with it.
In time, through bits and pieces of acceptance, however, we see that we cannot maintain the past intact. It has been forever changed and we must readjust.
Finding acceptance may be just having more good days than bad ones.
As we begin to live again and enjoy our life, we often feel that in doing so, we are betraying our loved one.
Instead of denying our feelings, listen to your needs. we move, we change, we grow, we evolve.
We begin to live again, but we cannot do so until we have given grief its time.
Children and teens need and want the truth as much as adults do.
Do Not Present Information about a death over the Public Address, P.A., system. It is impersonal.
After a death, especially a violent death, people may be wondering how to stay safe and to take care of themselves.
Each person approaches death in their own way, bringing to this last experience their uniqueness.
There are many roads arriving at the same destination.
It might feel particularly lonely because we’re all having to isolate ourselves from one another.
A therapist can help you make real meaning of your feelings and the experiences you’ve had both in the past and now.
See the loss and its significance and slowly begin to accept its reality. 
Allow yourself to experience the pain of your loss and give yourself the time to heal and adjust to the new reality.
#
# Mortenhoe
# 
She saw herself dead. the bundle of neurons changed.
Dead was dead. utter. incomprehensible.
Dead was nowhere.
Dead wasn't coffins, mourners, crematories. Dead was an intolerable nowhere.
Dead was a place, the no place, she'd be at.
Organisms wore out, broke down, stopped. There was nothing to make a song and dance about.
Is it vulgar to want to be cosseted in my declining weeks?
Soon you're going to die. you're going to get iller and iller, and finally - die. That's what you ought to be thinking about.
They were, I though, too young to die.
I wished authorities would give them whatever they want and let ordinary people get on with their lives - and deaths - in peace.
From a find to a check, from a check to a view, from a view to a death in the morning.
It's funny how some people are in the news for the way they live, while others achieve fame only in the fashion of their dying.
#
# Philosophy
#
There is no deeper narrative that makes sense of it all, much as we'd like to believe there is. It's all just chance and happenstance.
We live in a society that fears anger.
Death gives value to life.
Death is hard, but part of life. We can only accept.
The question is not 'How long did you live?'. The question is 'Did you give?'.
We can't forget someone so we don't truly lose them.
What's the most important lesson when you lose someone?
Grievers often feel abandoned by friends in the midst of their loss.
So often as well meaning friends, co-workers and loved ones , we don't know what to say to a person who has just experienced a loss so we say nothing at all.
Often teens not only deal with the loss of a parent, but also have to take on many more responsibilities around the house which often leads to feelings of resentment on top of their raw grief.
While we know nothing for certain about what happens before we are born or after we die, death marks an unavoidable destination in the path of every human being.
Death can be a relieving certainty or a looming threat.
Many philosophers have written extensive works on the matter. Some of these perspectives are essential for understanding the intellectual development of western civilization.
Concerning the philosophy of death, first, we discuss what it is to be alive.
#Socrates
The immortality of the soul is a very important point of Socratic philosophy as a whole and the core aspect of his views on death itself.
In nature we can clearly observe that life emerges from death and decay – and so must the soul, which survives our physical death and eventually returns as a new life.
According to Socrates, immortality can be proved by arguments resting on the existence of the cycle of life.
Socrates insists that while our lives are to be cherished as gifts of the gods death is not an evil thing that we should fear.
If you live your life as a moral person your soul should be in balance, and death is simply the natural way to free your soul and guide it to the eternal truths.
Death is seen as the liberation of the soul and that is why it should be faced with serenity.
The Socratic perspective on death is a beautiful way of viewing the end of our lives.
#Decartes
Ever since Ancient times it was understood that body and soul consisted in two parts of the same entity.
Descartes claimed that the body and the soul were separate entities that merely interacted with each other. The immortal soul persists as consciousness after the end.
The immortal soul persists as consciousness after the end of our physiological functions, because existence after death wouldn't make sense without a mind to verify such existence.
The established conception up until that point was that death consisted in the decay of the physical body and the departure of the soul.
