Vitalism is a nonstarter since it is unclear what sort of stuff vitalists take life to be, and because no likely candidates — no special stuff found in all and only living things — have been detected.
Sometimes when we speak of a life we mean to refer to the events that make up something's history — the things that it did and the things that happened to it.
We want clarification of what it is to be alive.
If lives are biological events, it would be useful to know more about what they are, how they are individuated, and what their persistence conditions are.
Life-functionalism, a view introduced by Aristotle, analyzes the property alive in terms of one or more salient functions that living things typically are able to perform.
We might adopt NASA's definition, according to which life is a self-sustaining chemical system capable of Darwinian evolution.
Feldman concludes that life is a mystery.
A live object has a distinctive sort of control over whether things come to be, or cease to be, part of it.
The event by which the capacity to engage in vital activities is lost is one thing, and the state of affairs of its having been lost it is another.
In some cases dying is especially complicated, because the self-modifying activities of some organisms result in the construction of complex physiological systems that must remain largely intact for the self-modifying activities of these organisms to remain integrated.
In defining death, some theorists focus on systems, and claim that an organism's life ends when that organism's physiological systems can no longer function as an integrated whole.
They are not dead, but are they alive?
When we say that something is dead, we mean to emphasize that a capacity has been lost.
People often speak of being dead as a ‘state' or ‘condition' as opposed to an event or process.
Some theorists deny that an object that is at one time an organism may continue its existence as a corpse. Such theorists will say that organisms and their corpses are two different objects.
Imagine a futuristic device that chops me into small cubes, or individual cells, or disconnected atoms, which it stores and later reassembles just as they were. It is far from obvious that I would survive.
I would not live during intervals when my atoms are stacked in storage. I would not even exist during such intervals.
Restoration, not revival, is a way of bringing a creature back from the dead.
Dying is the loss of an object's life—the loss of its capacity to perpetuate itself using vital activities. An object dies at the time it loses this capacity. It is dead at all times afterwards, except while that capacity is regained.
If we are animals, with the persistence conditions of animals, we die when we cease to be the same animal.
If we are minds, with the persistence conditions for minds, we die when we cease to meet these conditions.
If persistence is determined by our retaining certain psychological features, then the loss of those features will constitute death.
The mind could survive the extinction of the human animal.
The term termination refers to the view that when a person dies, he or she … goes out of existence; subsequently, there is no such thing as that person.
Even in morgues calling something a dead person does not imply that it is a person.
Can creatures cease to exist without dying? Certainly things that never were alive, such as bubbles and statues, can be deathlessly annihilated.
If people could divide like amoebas, perhaps they, too could cease to exist without dying.
Nothing can be alive unless it exists, so if something ceases to exist it ceases to be alive, but to cease to be alive is to die. So there are no deathless exits.
Defining death is one thing; providing criteria by which it can be readily detected or verified is another.
Some adopted criteria for the death of a person modeled on the Uniform Determination of Death Act.
A determination of death must be made in accordance with accepted medical standards.
Animalists might resist the criteria since the vital activities of human beings whose entire brains have ceased to function can be sustained artificially using cardiopulmonary assistance. 
Mindists and personists might also resist the criteria, on the grounds that minds and all psychological features can be destroyed in human beings whose brain stems are intact.
Is death bad for some people who die? Is it good for some of them?
The better life is, we think, the better more life would be, and the worse death is. At this point, we are in danger of condemning the human condition, which embraces life and death.
Life has a tragic side, namely death.
It is no wonder that theorists over the millennia have sought to defeat the harm thesis.
When we are, death is not, and when death is present, then we are not.
Death is to be deprived of sensation.
Make yourself familiar with the belief that death is nothing to us, since everything good and bad lies in sensation.
If a person's death is not an experience at all, clearly it is not an experience that is intrinsically good or bad for her.
A person may experience dying, and the experience of dying might well be intrinsically bad.
The question arises as to whether, for some people, it is extrinsically bad to die.
Dying is wholly a matter of indifference for those who do not experience it, say because they sleep through it.
Suppose that I desire that my child have a happy upbringing, and it turns out that I am the only one who can make this happen, but I die suddenly, and as a consequence she has a miserable childhood.
Arguably, my untimely death would be bad for me, in that it would thwart my desire, even if I die in my sleep, and am never aware of her fate.
Comparativism might say that death is bad for us because of the goods it deprives us of, and not, or at least not always, because of any intrinsic evils for which it is responsible.
When, in particular, does dying painlessly make a person worse off?
But if this is the reason we cannot ascribe misfortune to a victim of death then we cannot even ascribe death to any victim.
You are your (joyless) corpse at time two.
Now, it does make sense to attribute the property lacks joy to a corpse, and to a person who has stopped existing.
The same seems true of us during such times as we are no longer alive — times when we have become corpses or when those corpses have turned to dust.
Death takes a person out of actual existence, the dead are not 'there' to be harmed.
Modal realism with the thesis of transworld identity says that although a dead person no longer exists in the actual world, one and the same person is still alive, and exists, in other possible worlds.
