Knowledge of death and the encounter with it
The question of death is repressed, rejected and avoided by Freud.
He found the phenomenon of people involuntarily subjecting themselves to disturbing stimuli would be irreconcilable with the pleasure principle.
Many of us have endured significant upheavals which has made grief and frustration a constant
Both responses, mourning and melancholia, look similar in terms of mood or expression because they both deal with grief. 
Mourning, in Freud's view, is a finite and transforming painful process.
Melancholia is a persistent state, and takes root just outside of a person's conscious understanding
In mourning, a person feels their pain for the loss in an external way. 
The world around them may feel changed, bleak, or heartbreaking, but as they allow themselves to feel and process this change, they can reform their feelings of loss.
Pain slowly turns into a positive motivation to replace or move away from what they’ve understood is gone.
Mourning is a process that ends with a kind of acceptance.
Pain of object loss in melancholia is felt within the unconscious.
Meaning that the significance of the loss isn't quite so apparent to the griever, even though the pain of it might still be deeply felt. 
This can result in ego attacks, where the pain of loss and conflict gets turned inward, harming the sense of self.
They start to worry that the loss means something awful about them.
This triggers shame and worthlessness, and they start to feel like they can't tell anybody about it for fear their friends or family will realize how unlikable or useless they really are.
They start to feel like all their losses are their own fault and internalize that feeling of being bad.
The feelings become so unbearable and generalized that they become part of the person's unconscious.
This is the effect of melancholia.
Involve talking with someone they trust about the loss, expressing their pain and anger.
It can be easier to talk with a therapist about their anger, anxiety, and ego attacks than it is with someone they know personally.
What Freud suggests is that, rather than holding the pain and anxiety of loss inside, properly mourning a loss occurs when we have a chance to make sense of it.
we make sense of our feelings by verbalizing them to someone who is really listening and trying to understand.
Taking the time to specify and understand the feelings we have due to loss and grief is one of the best and most immediate ways to keep our feelings from getting buried and left unprocessed.
Pathological grief is far more complex and worsens with time. It lingers and intensifies and traps your mind in overwhelming sadness and guilt.
What's truly fascinating about melancholia is how it shapes your life and influences your mental health without your realization.
it's an interesting portrait of the unconscious and its role in keeping unresolved feelings alive.
Unconscious grief, you will realize, is more than an emotional wound. It's your psyche's internal turmoil.
According to Freud, mourning releases libido through gradual detachment to form new attachments.
In melancholia, libido regresses into the ego, prevents withdrawal, and merges with the qualities of the lost person or object.
The result is self-destructive and hostile, and increases internal conflict, which results in pathological grief.
